avia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ieuan ap Rhirid was born about 1333, in Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Rhirid ap Adda. He married Gwenllian ferch Cynwrig about 1350, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"ABT    1333–":"umbes 1333–Surnud","1333–Male":"1333–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1358–Male":"1358–Surnud","–1334":"–1334","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","ABT    1333":"umbes 1333","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","ABT    1358":"umbes 1358","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","of,Rhoscolyn,Anglesey,Wales":"Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT    1333–":"noin 1333–Kuollut","1333–Male":"1333–Kuollut","1329–Female":"1329–Kuollut","1358–Male":"1358–Kuollut","–1334":"–1334","1308–Male":"1308–Kuollut","Abt 1350":"noin 1350","ABT    1333":"noin 1333","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","ABT    1358":"noin 1358","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of,Rhoscolyn,Anglesey,Wales":"Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT    1333–":"environ 1333–Décédé","1333–Male":"1333–Décédé","1329–Female":"1329–Décédée","1358–Male":"1358–Décédé","–1334":"–1334","1308–Male":"1308–Décédé","Abt 1350":"environ 1350","ABT    1333":"environ 1333","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","ABT    1358":"environ 1358","Wales":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","of,Rhoscolyn,Anglesey,Wales":"Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Ieuan ap Rhirid est né environ 1333, à Rhoscolyn, Gwynedd, P